[2026-06-10] v0.5.0: Standardizing National Gate Boilerplates
1. Implementation & Changes (What)
Introduced the Official Starter Kit (boilerplate/index.html): Embedded a globally standardized frontend template into the core repository, allowing new participating nations to instantly deploy their own independent, standalone Gates.

Automated Data Injection: Integrated a core script that dynamically parses local gate_config.json files and era-specific policy JSONs (including funding_sockets economic metadata) to automatically render them onto the grid UI.

Universal Economic Layer (P2P Remittance) Support: Implemented a shared component logic that automatically calculates the defined developer role distribution (Scribes, Auditors, Architects) from any nation's JSON, dynamically generating a matching color bar and tip buttons on the fly.

2. Design Intent & Background (Why)
① Preventing National Development Teams from "Reinventing the Wheel"
Allowing every newly established nation (e.g., Gate 33 French Sector, Gate 49 German Sector) to write frontend UIs and merge logic from scratch is highly inefficient and creates a breeding ground for data format deviations (bugs).
By distributing design and logic in a pre-standardized "vessel," international contributors can acquire a cutting-edge 2026 cyber dashboard immediately—simply by filling out and placing their local policy JSONs.

② Enforcement of "Data Sovereignty (Decentralization)"
This template is not served from a centralized server; it runs completely "standalone" on each nation's own repository infrastructure (such as GitHub Pages).
As a result, even if the core server (kashika-core) goes physically offline or faces censorship from a specific nation, individual national gates will continue to survive and operate independently across the globe.

[2026-06-10] v0.4.0: Economic Layer Design (Initial Volunteer-Driven + Static Donation Sockets)
1. Implementation & Changes (What)
"Honor-First" Initial Operations (Volunteer-Driven): Direct cash rewards are set to "zero" across the board at launch. Incentives for contribution are restricted strictly to building "Reputation Balance on Web3/GitHub" via permanent inscriptions into the data logs (SBT/contributors arrays).

Specifications for Decentralized "Donation Sockets": Statically defined an object field inside national gates (kashika-gate-XX) and individual policy JSON nodes, allowing contributors to embed public addresses/links to accept direct donations.

Preliminary Design for Performance-Based "Automated Peer Bonuses": Articulated the philosophy for a payment pipeline where if a donor wishes to directly tip the specific "Scribe" who unearthed a piece of policy data, the funds land directly in their wallet without routing through a centralized management entity.

2. Design Intent & Background (Why)
① Pre-Debugging the Bug of Monetary-Driven "Data Spam"
If we were to design incentives like "earn X dollars per JSON entry" from the beginning, the system would be flooded with spam—garbage data generated by ChatGPT, packed with adjectives and lacking primary sources—forcing its way into merges and collapsing the verification capacity of our Auditors.
By relying solely on "honor and geek pride" during the initial phase, we ensure the purity of early-stage data remains 100% "Facts Only."

② Refusing a Centralized Wallet (Nullifying Borders and Transaction Fees)
The moment a global control tower (kashika-core) pools international donations to distribute them later, we resurrect political disputes over bank transfer fees, foreign exchange risks, local tax compliance, and "suspicions of administrative skim-offs."
Therefore, KASHIKA holds no wallet (central account) to pool funds. The flow of money must mirror the architecture of the system: a flat, peer-to-peer connection from supporter to contributor.

③ Sockets Delivering "Data Gratitude" Directly to Engineers
For example, if a Japanese think tank or civic group realizes, "Thanks to this Taiwanese policy data log, we caught a bug in our new Japanese bill beforehand! Thank you!", we provide a structure (socket) at the end of the JSON so they can push a donation directly to the Taiwanese team's wallet (or Open Collective). This allows a volunteer Scribe to discover autonomous economic returns later, noticing that "tips are organically trickling in based on historical contribution logs."

