[2026-06-10] v0.3.0: Separation of Concerns and Establishing the Global Data Call Network
Decoupling the global dashboard (kashika-core) from national gates (such as kashika-gate-81), and implementing "Wanted Logs" and the "Direct Data Request" GitHub Issue pipeline.

To ensure that future contributors completely grasp the context of this project-defining shift—the complete decoupling of the core system and the establishment of a global data request network—this historical evolution has been formatted to overwrite or append directly into the latest version of kashika-core/CHANGELOG.md.

1. Implementation & Changes (What)
Complete Decoupling of the Core Architecture:

Japan Sector (kashika-gate-81): Specialized to handle domestic local ledgers across eras (Modern, GHQ, Imperial) and optimize domestic viewer UIs.

Global Control Tower (kashika-core): Created a top-level dashboard (dashboard.html) responsible for indexing independent national gates, global data matching, and cross-border data requests.

Deployment of the "Wanted Logs" System: For domestic policies flagged by the internal assertion engine as "lacking empirical evidence," we implemented a link-submission merge feature on the global board. This allows geeks and researchers worldwide to drop primary source URLs directly into the platform to reinforce the grid structure.

Opening the "Direct Data Request (Data Call)" Pipeline: Embedded a live integration emulator where clicking "💬 Direct Data Request" from a national gate registry automatically populates the title and body parameters, jumping users directly to that nation's GitHub repository Issue creation screen.

2. Design Intent & Background (Why)
① Separation of Concerns Between National Gates and the Global Board
Bundling all functionalities into the Japanese Gate or a single monolithic repository would have bloated the project, centralized authority, and introduced bugs compromising the sovereignty (autonomous execution) of international sectors.
By enforcing a strict separation—"National Gates manage domestic data on local repositories" and "The Core handles global cross-referencing and allocation of missing data"—we finalized a structure where any nation on Earth can plug into the grid on equal footing.

② Visualizing Scarcity to the World (Wanted Logs)
Simply asking people to "come aggregate open-source data" leaves contributors paralyzed, unsure of what to scribe.
By exposing a state of scarcity on the global board—e.g., "Right now, to logically back up this Japanese policy, we are missing the exact empirical metrics from Taiwan's XX project or its equivalent public document URL!"—we clarify the precise target parameters for Scribes across the globe.

③ Zero-Friction International Data Calls (GitHub Integration)
Even if a contributor wants to ask an international gate (e.g., Estonia Team 372) "Do you have this data?", communication friction and varying open-source etiquette act as barriers.
By engineering a pipeline that lands directly inside the target country's GitHub Issues with the requirements pre-written at the click of a button, we refactored cross-border data requests down to near-zero friction.

3. Technical Stack (Memorandum)
Interface Decoupling: kashika-core/index.html functions as the global control tower, dynamically projecting URL parameters to the Issue endpoints of national repositories (kashika-gate-[code]).

Data Structure Binding: URLs provided in response to global "Wanted" cards are temporarily held under an Auditing status. They simulate a flow where they are formally merged into the core protocol matrix only after receiving validation from an Auditor.

Driving Principle: "Gates run autonomously in isolation; the Core links them via the grid. The data the world demands (Wanted) is resolved through the link-merges of available geeks worldwide."

[2026-06-10] v0.2.0: The Great Shift from Hierarchical Pyramids to a Parallel Matrix (Grid)
1. Implementation & Changes (What)
Designed a Minimal Starter Kit for International Sectors: Formulated a repository blueprint allowing national gates (e.g., kashika-gate-886 Taiwan Team) to boot up autonomously within 3 minutes simply by placing an index.json and an eras/ directory directly under their root.

Defined 3 Parallel Autonomous Roles (Reward Layer): Eradicated hierarchical rankings entirely. Explicitly defined flat gameplay mechanics where participants choose their own specialization (SCRIBE / AUDITOR / ARCHITECT), engraving immutable honor onto the data logs themselves via SBT/contributors inscriptions.

Published the Global Contributing Guide: Deployed a comprehensive CONTRIBUTING.md detailing the core philosophies and JSON schemas so that international contributors can fork and open gates immediately without confusion.

Implemented Frontend Viewer Merge Engine: Refactored the core logic of the Japan Gate (kashika-gate-81/index.html). Injected a decompilation engine that dynamically fetches JSON structures (impact_logs) from other national gates linked by Architects, parallel-rendering them on-screen as a "data-driven endorsement log."

2. Design Intent & Background (Why)
① Maximizing Agility by Eliminating "Hierarchies"
The originally proposed hierarchical reward design (incentivizing via points and rank-ups) threatened to create centralized community management costs, generating a predictable bug: psychological friction and barriers to entry for international geeks and experts.
By refactoring into a "Parallel Matrix" where all members collaborate horizontally as equals, we laid down a true open-source foundation where international teams can participate with absolute fluidity, thinking, "Hey, let me try dropping my country's data in there too."

② "Data-Driven Backup (Grid Binding)" to Eliminate Emotional Rhetoric
When introducing a new policy, public debate often devolves into subjective arguments and emotional mudslinging (a futile exchange of adjectives).
In response, we engineered a structure that cross-links the empirical metrics of other nations' historical records into a grid layout on a "Facts Only" basis (with primary sources and zero adjectives).
This allows the system to automatically generate undeniable logical backing and structural evidence: "This 2026 Japanese proposal shares the exact structural blueprint as Taiwan's 2015 data (vTaiwan) and Estonia's 2005 data (i-Voting)—therefore, it is structurally sound and should be enacted."

3. Technical Stack (Memorandum)
Data Structure: Eras declaration via index.json for each gate, paired with complete decoupling of Before/After empirical data using the impact_logs array inside each individual policy JSON.

Merge Engine: Triggered by the crossGateFetchPointer object inside the localRegistry, the engine dynamically analyzes fact data from external repositories and binds them into HTML tables as a unified grid.

Driving Principle: "We do not determine approval or opposition based on emotion. The historical data of other nations' pasts proves the specifications of another nation's future."
